---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../components/PageHeader.astro';
import InfoBox from '../components/InfoBox.astro';
import FactCard from '../components/FactCard.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Puppy Care Guide | Harris Heritage Cavaliers"
  description="Essential care tips for your new Cavalier King Charles Spaniel puppy. Feeding, grooming, exercise, and health advice from Harris Heritage Cavaliers."
  keywords="Cavalier puppy care, Cavalier King Charles Spaniel care guide, puppy feeding guide, Cavalier grooming"
>
  <PageHeader
    title="Puppy Care Guide"
    subtitle="Everything you need to know to give your new Cavalier King Charles Spaniel puppy the best start in life."
  />

  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="content-container">
      <h2>Caring for Your New Cavalier Puppy</h2>
      <p>Congratulations on your new Cavalier King Charles Spaniel! Here is a comprehensive guide to help you provide the best care for your new family member.</p>

      <h3>Feeding</h3>
      <p>A healthy diet is the foundation of your puppy's well-being. We recommend a high-quality puppy food formulated for small breeds.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>8-12 weeks:</strong> Feed 3-4 small meals per day</li>
        <li><strong>3-6 months:</strong> Feed 3 meals per day</li>
        <li><strong>6-12 months:</strong> Transition to 2 meals per day</li>
        <li><strong>Adult:</strong> Continue with 2 meals per day</li>
      </ul>

      <InfoBox type="tip" title="Food Transition">
        <p>We send a sample of the food your puppy is currently eating in the welcome kit. Gradually transition to your chosen food over 7-10 days to avoid digestive upset. Mix increasing amounts of the new food with decreasing amounts of the current food.</p>
      </InfoBox>

      <h3>Grooming</h3>
      <p>Cavalier King Charles Spaniels have a beautiful medium-length, silky coat that requires regular maintenance.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Brushing:</strong> Brush 2-3 times per week to prevent mats, especially around the ears and feathering</li>
        <li><strong>Bathing:</strong> Bathe every 2-4 weeks or as needed</li>
        <li><strong>Ears:</strong> Check and clean ears weekly — Cavaliers are prone to ear infections due to their floppy ears</li>
        <li><strong>Nails:</strong> Trim nails every 2-3 weeks</li>
        <li><strong>Teeth:</strong> Brush teeth several times per week with dog-safe toothpaste</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Exercise</h3>
      <p>Cavaliers are moderately active dogs who enjoy daily walks and playtime. They are adaptable to both active and relaxed lifestyles.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Puppies: Short play sessions throughout the day (avoid overexertion)</li>
        <li>Adults: 30-60 minutes of exercise daily</li>
        <li>Great activities: walks, fetch, agility, and simply cuddling on the couch</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Health Considerations</h3>
      <p>While Cavaliers are generally healthy dogs, there are some breed-specific health considerations to be aware of:</p>

      <div class="facts-grid">
        <FactCard title="Heart Health">
          Mitral Valve Disease is the most common concern. Regular cardiac checkups are recommended starting at age 1.
        </FactCard>
        <FactCard title="Eye Care">
          Annual eye exams can detect early signs of cataracts or other conditions common in the breed.
        </FactCard>
        <FactCard title="Joint Health">
          Maintain a healthy weight to reduce stress on joints. Patellar luxation screening is recommended.
        </FactCard>
        <FactCard title="Ear Health">
          Their long, floppy ears require regular cleaning to prevent infections. Keep ears dry and clean.
        </FactCard>
      </div>

      <h3>Socialization & Training</h3>
      <p>Cavaliers are eager to please and respond well to positive reinforcement training. Early socialization is key to developing a confident, well-adjusted adult dog.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Begin basic obedience training immediately using positive methods</li>
        <li>Expose your puppy to different people, animals, sounds, and environments</li>
        <li>Start crate training early — your puppy has already begun crate training basics with us</li>
        <li>Enroll in a puppy kindergarten class for structured socialization</li>
      </ul>

      <InfoBox type="info" title="Lifetime Support">
        <p>Remember, Harris Heritage Cavaliers offers lifetime breeder support. If you ever have questions about your puppy's care, health, or behavior, please do not hesitate to <a href="/contact">reach out to us</a>. We are always here to help!</p>
      </InfoBox>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .content-section {
    padding: 4rem 1.5rem;
    background: white;
  }

  .content-container {
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .content-container h2 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    color: #2C3E6B;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .content-container h3 {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    color: #2C3E6B;
    margin: 2rem 0 1rem;
  }

  .content-container p {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: #555;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .content-container ul {
    margin: 1rem 0 1.5rem 1.5rem;
    padding: 0;
  }

  .content-container li {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: #555;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .content-container li strong {
    color: #2a2a2a;
  }

  .content-container a {
    color: #2C3E6B;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  .facts-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    gap: 1.5rem;
    margin: 1.5rem 0 2rem;
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .content-section {
      padding: 3rem 1rem;
    }

    .content-container h2 {
      font-size: 1.5rem;
    }

    .facts-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
